        <content type="html">
            <![CDATA[
                
    <figure class="post__image post__image--center">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://www.vidabuenaacres.com/media/posts/6/Maggie-small.jpeg" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://www.vidabuenaacres.com/media/posts/6/responsive/Maggie-small-xs.jpeg 300w ,https://www.vidabuenaacres.com/media/posts/6/responsive/Maggie-small-sm.jpeg 480w ,https://www.vidabuenaacres.com/media/posts/6/responsive/Maggie-small-md.jpeg 768w ,https://www.vidabuenaacres.com/media/posts/6/responsive/Maggie-small-lg.jpeg 1024w ,https://www.vidabuenaacres.com/media/posts/6/responsive/Maggie-small-xl.jpeg 1360w ,https://www.vidabuenaacres.com/media/posts/6/responsive/Maggie-small-2xl.jpeg 1600w"  height="4032" width="3024" alt="" />
      
    </figure>

    <h2 id="grass-247">
      Grass 24/7
    </h2>

  <p>
    If our sheep were to have a motto, it would be "<i>Grass24/7</i>". Through rain, Texas heat, and winter blasts, our flock weathers it all out on the field. We provide ample grass and shelter, while they help recycle the nutrients to the soil.<br>
  </p>

    <h2 id="qualities">
      Qualities
    </h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Pasture raised on grass - no supplemental grain</li><li>Certified Organic Icelandic Kelp, and Loose Minerals provided free-choice for nutrition</li><li>Rotated daily through fresh pasture</li>
  </ul>

    <h2 id="hair-sheep">
      Hair Sheep
    </h2>

  <p>
    We run only hair sheep at LVBA, including a mix of Dorper, Katahdin, and St. Croix breeds. These breeds are resistant to parasites and do very well living on grass. They are also capable mothers - they lamb in the field with only minimal help on our end.
  </p>

  <p>
    Different from what we naturally think of in sheep, hair sheep do not produce a thick wool that requires shearing. Every spring they shed their winter coat, which often happens in bunches and patches that leaves them looking rather disheveled.&nbsp;
  </p>

  <p>
    This is their magic - they do their thing and we enjoy the zen of watching sheep munch on grass.&nbsp;
  </p>

